Using practical example scripts is an excellent way to illustrate the power of web development and help students see the direct result of their efforts. By providing a concrete example, you can make complex concepts more accessible and engaging.

**The Importance of Examples in Education**

1. **Concrete understanding**: Examples help students develop a concrete understanding of abstract concepts, making it easier for them to grasp and apply the knowledge.
2. **Contextualization**: Examples provide context, helping students see how the concepts they're learning are used in real-world applications.
3. **Motivation**: Seeing the direct result of their efforts can be a powerful motivator, encouraging students to continue learning and exploring.
4. **Reinforcement**: Examples can reinforce learning by providing a tangible representation of the concepts, making it easier for students to recall and apply the knowledge.

**Example Script: Saving User-Inputted Text**

Here's a simple example script that demonstrates how a form can accept and save user-inputted text using JavaScript, HTML, and CSS:
```html
<!-- index.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Form Example</title>
  <style>
    /* Add some basic styling to make the form look nice */
    form {
      width: 50%;
      margin: 40px auto;
      padding: 20px;
      border: 1px solid #ccc;
      border-radius: 10px;
      box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Form Example</h1>
  <form id="myForm">
    <label for="name">Name:</label>
    <input type="text" id="name" name="name"><br><br>
    <label for="message">Message:</label>
    <textarea id="message" name="message"></textarea><br><br>
    <input type="submit" value="Submit">
  </form>
  <div id="result"></div>

  <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

```javascript
// script.js
// Get the form and result elements
const form = document.getElementById('myForm');
const result = document.getElementById('result');

// Add an event listener to the form's submit event
form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  // Prevent the default form submission behavior
  e.preventDefault();

  // Get the user-inputted text
  const name = document.getElementById('name').value;
  const message = document.getElementById('message').value;

  // Save the user-inputted text to local storage
  localStorage.setItem('name', name);
  localStorage.setItem('message', message);

  // Display the saved text in the result element
  result.innerHTML = `Name: ${name}<br>Message: ${message}`;
});
```
This example script demonstrates how to:

1. Create a simple form with input fields and a submit button.
2. Add an event listener to the form's submit event.
3. Get the user-inputted text and save it to local storage.
4. Display the saved text in the result element.

